transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Hello, thank you for participating in this interview. I'm going to ask you some questions about your health and experiences. Let's begin.

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Hello, thank you for having me. I’m ready to answer your questions.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me a bit about yourself and your current life situation?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Sure! I’m Leah, and I’m 22 years old. I’m currently a college student, but I don’t have a degree yet. I also work part-time, but my job is pretty flexible, so I can manage my school schedule. I live in a rural area in Maine, which can feel a bit isolating sometimes. My family comes from a low-income background, and I’m on Medicaid for health insurance. Honestly, I don’t really think about my health that much, and I don’t see a doctor regularly. I do smoke occasionally and drink socially with friends, but I’m not planning on getting pregnant right now. I use condoms for contraception. I guess that’s a little about me!

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Can you tell me about your pregnancy or pregnancies? When did you first learn you were pregnant?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: I haven't been pregnant before, so I don't have any personal experiences with that. I'm currently not planning on getting pregnant either. I use condoms for contraception to make sure of that. It’s something I think about occasionally, especially since I’m still in school and focused on my studies and work.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: When did you first seek prenatal care? What was that experience like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: Well, since I haven't been pregnant, I haven't actually sought out any prenatal care. I know that it's important for those who are pregnant, but for me, I just haven’t had that experience. Sometimes I think about how I might feel if I were to get pregnant, and I imagine I would want to make sure I had good care, but right now, it’s not something I have to deal with. 

Interviewer: That makes sense. It’s good that you’re thinking about these things. If you were to find out you were pregnant, do you feel like you would know where to go for care or support? 

Persona: I guess I would try to find a local clinic or maybe ask friends who have been pregnant or had kids. But honestly, I’m not sure how easy it would be to get that kind of care around here. The healthcare resources feel limited, especially living in a rural area. I would be a bit worried about finding the right information and support. 

Interviewer: I understand that can be a concern. Have you ever had any discussions with healthcare providers about family planning or contraception? 

Persona: Not really. I’ve had a couple of check-ups when I was younger, but I don’t think I ever really talked about family planning. It’s just not something that comes up often for me. I mostly just use condoms, and that’s been my way of handling things. 

Interviewer: Thank you for sharing that. Sometimes discussions about family planning can be challenging, especially if there’s limited access to healthcare. Do you feel comfortable talking to someone, like a healthcare provider, about your health and any concerns you might have?

Persona: I mean, I’d probably be a bit nervous talking to someone about my health. I don’t see doctors often, and I’m not really sure how to start those kinds of conversations. I feel like I wouldn’t even know what questions to ask. 

Interviewer: That’s completely understandable; many people feel that way. If you did have questions or concerns, what would you want to know about your health or family planning?

Persona: I think I would want to know more about what my options are if I ever did get pregnant. Like, what kind of care I would need and how to take care of myself and the baby. I’d also want to know about any risks or things I should be aware of, especially since I don’t see a doctor often. 

Interviewer: Those are very important questions. It’s good to be informed about your options and health. Have you had any experiences with healthcare that have shaped how you view seeking care or using services in general?

Persona: I guess my experiences have been pretty limited. I’ve gone to the clinic a few times when I was younger, but I haven’t had any major health issues or anything that required me to go more often. Sometimes I feel like it’s hard to make time for it with school and work. Plus, living in a rural area makes it feel like a hassle to get to a doctor. 

Interviewer: That’s a valid concern, balancing school, work, and healthcare access can be really challenging. Are there any barriers you feel prevent you from seeking healthcare more regularly?

Persona: Yeah, definitely. Time is a big one, and then there’s the travel distance. I also worry about costs, even with Medicaid; sometimes I hear stories about people having trouble with getting care or the costs of certain services. It makes me hesitant to even look into it. 

Interviewer: It sounds like there are several factors at play. Thank you for sharing your thoughts and experiences with me, Leah. It’s important to acknowledge these barriers. Are there any resources or support systems you think might help you feel more comfortable seeking care if you needed it in the future? 

Persona: Honestly, I’m not sure what resources are out there. I hear about some programs, but I don’t know how to access them. I think if there were more information available or if there were local support groups, that might help. Just knowing what’s out there would make a difference. 

Interviewer: That’s a great insight. Having access to information and support can really empower individuals to take charge of their health. Thank you for sharing all of this with me. Is there anything else you’d like to add about your health or experiences that we haven’t covered?

Persona: I think we’ve covered a lot, but I just hope that more people like me can find the help they need, especially in rural areas. It can feel really isolating not knowing where to go for support. 

Interviewer: Thank you for expressing that concern, Leah. Your thoughts are very important, and I appreciate you being open during this interview. If you have any questions or need support in the future, please don’t hesitate to reach out to local resources or healthcare providers.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: Who is providing your prenatal care? Can you describe your relationship with your healthcare provider?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text: Persona: Since I haven't been pregnant, I don't have any prenatal care or a healthcare provider specifically for that. I’ve only had a couple of check-ups when I was younger. I think if I did have a provider, I would hope for someone who understands my background and is patient with me. I would want to feel comfortable asking questions and not feel rushed during appointments. Building that kind of relationship seems really important, especially if I were to need ongoing care. But right now, I don’t have that connection with any healthcare provider.

transcript.speaker: Interviewer
transcript.text: How often do you have prenatal appointments? Can you walk me through what a typical visit is like?

transcript.speaker: Persona
transcript.text:
Persona: Since I haven’t been pregnant, I don’t have any prenatal appointments to describe. But if I were to have them in the future, I imagine they would involve checking in on the health of both me and the baby. I think there would be a lot of questions about my health history, maybe some physical exams, and possibly some tests to monitor the baby’s development. I’d hope that the visits would be regular, maybe once a month or so, especially during the later stages of pregnancy. I think I’d like to have time to ask questions and discuss any concerns I might have, but since I haven’t experienced it, it’s hard to say for sure what it would be like. 

Interviewer: That sounds like a thoughtful way to approach it. If you did have prenatal appointments, what kind of questions or concerns do you think you would want to bring up during those visits?

Persona: I think I would want to ask about what to expect during pregnancy, like what changes I might experience in my body and how to maintain my health. I’d also be curious about the different tests and screenings that might be done, and how to prepare for labor and delivery. If I had any specific health concerns or worries, I would want to make sure to bring those up too. It would feel important to have those conversations to feel more prepared and supported. 

Interviewer: That’s a great approach to preparing for a potential pregnancy. It’s important to feel informed and supported during such a significant time. Have you thought about how you would prefer to receive information or support regarding pregnancy and maternal health?

Persona: I think I would prefer having a mix of information, like written materials or brochures that I could read at my own pace, along with having a healthcare provider I could talk to face-to-face. Sometimes it’s easier to understand things when you can ask questions right away. I’d also appreciate any resources about local support groups or classes that might help me connect with others who are going through the same experiences. 

Interviewer: That sounds like a well-rounded approach to finding information and support. It’s great to hear that you’re thinking about these aspects. Lastly, is there anything you would like to see improved in the healthcare system, particularly for young women like yourself in rural areas?

Persona: I think it would be really helpful to have more accessible resources and information tailored for young women, especially those in rural areas. Maybe more outreach programs that connect people with local healthcare options or even virtual resources that can be accessed easily. It would also be nice if there were more community events focused on health education, so people can learn and ask questions in a comfortable setting. Just making sure that everyone knows what’s out there and how to get it would really make a difference. 

Interviewer: Those are valuable suggestions. Thank you so much for sharing your thoughts and experiences, Leah. Your insights can help shape a better understanding of the needs in healthcare access and support for individuals like you. If you have any further thoughts or if anything comes up after this interview, please feel free to reach out. 

Persona: Thank you! I appreciate the opportunity to share my experiences. I hope it helps in some way.
